References

Basemaps

The basemap / basemaps are the underlying layers of map over which we are going to depict our data.

Leaflet supports basemaps using map tiles, which became prevalent thanks to google mas.

The default tile is OpenStreetMap and the following code is sufficient to load it:

# Initializes the map app and provides the necessary data
leaflet() %>% 
  
  # Adds a basemap
  addTiles()

Centering the initial view

The previous code initializes the map with a world view. We can give additional location and zoom level argumnts to change the initial view. For example, we may choose to focus the view on Madrid as follows (latitude and longitude corresponding to Puerta del Sol)

# Initializes the map app
leaflet() %>% 
  
  # Adds the basemap
  addTiles() %>%
  
  # Sets the view to specific latitude and longitude
  # Also adjust the zoom level
  setView(lat = 40.416904, lng =  -3.703556, zoom = 13)

Changing the aspect / aesthetics of the baseMap

We are not limited to the OpenStreetMaps basemap. In fact, leaflet provides a great amount of alternatives within the variable providers. Ussing the function addProviderTiles() we can select one of this suppliers shown below (I chose CartoDB.Positron because I like its minimalistic looks):

# Initializes the map app
leaflet() %>% 
  
  # Changes the basemap style
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>%
  
  # Sets the view and zoom level to specific latitude and longitude
  setView(lat = 40.416904, lng =  -3.703556, zoom = 13)

However, we are not limited to this either. A complete list of the providers can be obtained using names(providers). To help you pick one, there is a demonstration of each in this link. For example, look at the cool colored map below.

IMPORTANT note that we are storing the entire map in a variable called mymap, much like we could store a ggplot figure in a variable.

# Store the map in a variable
mymap <- 
  
# Initializaes the map app
leaflet() %>% 
  
  # Changes the basemap style
  addProviderTiles(providers$Stamen.Watercolor) %>% 
  
  # Sets the view to specific latitude, longitude. Also adjusts zoom
  setView(lat = 40.416904, lng =  -3.703556, zoom = 6)

Saving maps as an image and as an html file.

To save the map to a .html, multiple libraries are available. In my experience, the most reliable way is to combine the two functions below. For them to be available you need to load the libraries htmlwidgets and webshot. In this notebook, they are loaded at the beginning (section libraries). You may need to install this libraries once of you do not have them in your computer. The code is given as well on that section.

# Convert the map to a .html widtget.
# This is a temporal file
saveWidget(mymap, "iberian_peninsula.html", selfcontained = FALSE)

# Store the map as an image
webshot("iberian_peninsula.html", file = "iberian_peninsula_color.png",
        cliprect = "viewport")

'logical(1)'

Markers

Add a single marker

Let us add a single marker to signal Retiro’s Park in Madrid

# Initializes the map app
leaflet() %>% 
  
  # Changes the basemap style
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>% 
  
  # Adjust the view and zoom level to specific latitude and longitude
  setView(lat = 40.416904, lng =  -3.703556, zoom = 13) %>% 
  
  # Adds a marker at the specified latitude and longitude
  addMarkers(lat = 40.415463, lng = -3.683938)

Change the marker’s icon

We can actually change the icon on the marker with the functions addAwesomeMarkers() and addAwesomeIcons()

  • If we specify library = "glyphicon" we have access to the icons in this link
  • If we specify library = "fa" we have access to the icons in this link

Let us exmine the syntax below:

# Initializes the map application
t <- leaflet() %>% 
  
  # Changes the basemap style
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>% 
  
  # Centers the view and zoom level at specific latitude and longitude
  setView(lat = 40.416904, lng =  -3.703556, zoom = 13) %>% 
  
  # Adds an awesome marker at the specified location.
  addAwesomeMarkers(
      lat = 40.415463, lng = -3.683938, 
      icon = awesomeIcons(
      icon = 'home', # Specifies the icon
      iconColor = 'black', # Specifies the color
      library = 'glyphicon', # Specifies the library
      ))

Let us try another icon and change the marker color using the argument markerColor:

# Initializes the map application
leaflet() %>% 
  
  # Changes the base map
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>% 
  
  # Centers the view and zoom level at a specific latitude and longitude
  setView(lat = 40.416904, lng =  -3.703556, zoom = 13) %>% 
  
  # Adds a tower maker from gyplhicon libary.
  # Sets the market color to red and the iconcolor to black
  addAwesomeMarkers(
      lat = 40.415463, lng = -3.683938,
      icon = awesomeIcons(
      icon = 'tower',
      iconColor = 'black',
      library = 'glyphicon',
      markerColor = "red"
      ))

Add a set of coordinates to be found in a separate dataframe

We are going to load a dataframe inlcuding the name, latitude, longitude and number of visitors in the last hour to several touristic spots in Madrid:

coord <-
  read_csv("sites_coordinates.csv")

Let us inspect the dataframe:

coord
# A tibble: 5 × 4
  name                 lat   lon visitors
  <chr>              <dbl> <dbl>    <dbl>
1 Parque del Retiro   40.4 -3.68      400
2 Templo de Debod     40.4 -3.72      300
3 Santiago Bernabeu   40.5 -3.69       20
4 Dehesa de la Villa  40.5 -3.72      250
5 IE Tower            40.5 -3.69      100

Now when we initialize the map application with leaflet() we are going to pass this dataframe as an argument. The variables in this dataframe will be accesible to the subsequent map functions we use. We are going to do this passing as an argument the variables lat and lon from the dataframe coord as arguments to the function. For this, we will add a tilde symbol ~:

# Initialize map application and pass data.
leaflet(coord) %>% 
  
  # Change basemap style
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>% 
  
  # Add markers to the locations specified in coord.
  # ~lat means: "variable lat from the coord dataframe"
  # ~lon means: "variable lon from the coord dataframe"
  addAwesomeMarkers(
      lat = ~lat, lng = ~lon,
      icon = awesomeIcons(
      icon = 'flag',
      iconColor = 'black',
      library = 'glyphicon',
      markerColor = "red"
      ))

Change the color of the markers depending on the number of visitors to each site.

This part is a litte

getColor <- 
  
  # Defines a function that takes the dataset `coord`
  # as an argument
  function(coord) {
  
  # This code generates a vector of colors based on
  # the number of visitors with the conditions specified below
  sapply(coord$visitors, function(visitors) {
    
  if(visitors <= 100) {
    "green"
    
  } else {
    
    "red"
  } 
  })
}

# Obtain vector of colors (1 color per row of dataframe coord)
# using the function getColor previously created
icon_colors <- getColor(coord)

# Defines colors based on the previously determined colors
icons <- awesomeIcons(
      icon = 'flag',
      iconColor = 'black',
      library = 'glyphicon',
      markerColor = icon_colors
      )

# Initializes map application
leaflet(coord) %>% 
  
  # Initializes the basemap
  addTiles() %>%
  
  # Changes the basemap style
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>% 
  
  # Adds the previously defined icons at the
  # locations specified by the variables lat and lon
  # of the dataframe coord
  addAwesomeMarkers(
      lat = ~lat, lng = ~lon,
      icon = icons)

Add circles

Now instead of using markers, we are going to use circles using addCircleMarkers(). The radius of the circles was determined by trial an error, adapting it to the needs of the map.

# Initializes map application
# and feeds the data contained in coord
leaflet(coord) %>% 
  
  # Adds a basemap
  addTiles() %>%
  
  # Changes pasemap style
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>% 
  
  # Adds circles of radius 10 at the locations contained
  # in coord, indicated by the variables lat and lon.
  addCircleMarkers(
      radius = 10,
      lat = ~lat, lng = ~lon,
      stroke = TRUE,
      fillOpacity = 0.1)

Now we want to adapt the size of the circles to the number of visitors at each site. For this, we are going to use a function, much like before we used a function to determine the colors based on the number of visitors:

getRadius <- 
  
  # Defines a function that takes the dataset `coord`
  # as an argument
  function(coord) {
    
  # This code generates a vector of radiuses based on the
  # number of visitors with the formula specified below.
  # the exact factor 5 / 100 was determined by trial an error
  # to obtain a proper scale for the circles
  sapply(coord$visitors, function(visitors) {
    
      visitors/100 * 5  
    
    })
}

# Generates vector of radiuses based on the previously defined function
radiuses <- getRadius(coord)

# Initialize map application
leaflet(coord) %>% 
  
  # Add basemap
  addTiles() %>%
  
  # Change besmap style
  addProviderTiles(providers$CartoDB.Positron) %>% 
  
  # Add circle markers with radiuses matching the previosly
  # generatred vector of radiuses
  addCircleMarkers(
      radius = radiuses,
      lat = ~lat, lng = ~lon,
      stroke = FALSE,
      fillOpacity = 0.5,
      
      # Specifies the label that will appear on the map
      # bases on the variables name and visitors contained in the
      # dataframe coord
      label = ~paste0(name, " - visitors: ", visitors))
